<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Neugebauer Equations" class="currentChild" href="Neugebauer_Equations">Neugebauer Equations</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A set of three equations that are used in <a title="color proofing" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/color_proofing">color proofing</a> to predict the <a title="Red, Green, and Blue" href="Red,_Green,_and_Blue">red, green, and blue</a> reflectances that are likely to result from printed <a title="Halftone Dot" href="Halftone_Dot">halftone dot</a>s. The Neugebauer equations are based on the specific dot sizes used to make a particular reproduction, and are extraordinarily complicated to solve, and even then require more trial and error than anything. However, new computer models and software packages are replacing such trial-and-error methods. 
</p>
